nd || {{fb|Greece}} || 5\u20132 || Friendly\n|-\n| 34 || 26 April 1978 || Warsaw, Poland || {{fb|Bulgaria}} || 1\u20130 || Friendly\n|-\n| 35 || 6 June 1978 || [[Rosario]], Argentina || {{fb|Tunisia}} || 1\u20130 || [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]\n|-\n| 36 || 21 June 1978 || [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]], Argentina || {{fb|Brazil}} || 1\u20133 || 1978 FIFA World Cup\n|-\n| 37 || 6 September 1978 || [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Iceland || {{fb|Iceland}} || 2\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 1980 qualifying]]\n|-\n| 38 || 21 March 1979 || [[Algiers]], Algeria || {{fb|Algeria}} || 1\u20130 || Friendly\n|-\n| 39 || 4 April 1979 || Chorz\u00f3w, Poland || {{fb|Hungary}} || 1\u20131 || Friendly\n|-\n| 40 || 29 August 1979 || Warsaw, Poland || {{fb|Romania}} || 3\u20130 || Friendly\n|-\n| 41 || 26 March 1980 || [[Budapest]], Hungary || {{fb|Hungary}} || 1\u20132 || Friendly\n|-\n| 42 || 4 April 1980 || [[Brussels]], Belgium || {{fb|Belgium}} || 1\u20132 || Friendly\n|-\n| 43 || 22 June 1980 || Warsaw, Poland || {{fb|Iraq}} || 3\u20130 || Friendly\n|-\n| 44 || 29 June 1980 || [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil || {{fb|Brazil}} || 1\u20131 || Friendly\n|-\n| 45 || 22 June 1982 || [[A Coru\u00f1a]], Spain || {{fb|Peru}} || 5\u20131 || [[1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n[[File:Gwiazda lato.jpg|thumb|right|Lato's star in [[W\u0142adys\u0142awowo]], pictured in 2006]]\n\n===Club===\n'''Stal Mielec'''\n*[[Orange Ekstraklasa|Polish Premier League]]: 1973, 1976\n*[[Polish Cup]] finalist: 1976\n\n'''Atlante F.C.'''\n*[[CONCACAF Champions Cup]]: 1983\n\n''' Lokeren SC '''\n* [[Belgian Cup]] finalist: 1981\n\n'''Individual'''\n* Polish Premier League top scorer: 1973, 1975\n* ''Pi\u0142ka No\u017cna'' Player of the Year: 1977, 1981\n* ''Sport'' Player of the Year: 1974, 1977\n\n===International===\n'''Poland'''\n* Olympic gold medal: [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]]\n* Olympic silver medal: [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1976]]\n* [[FIFA World Cup]] \u2013 third place: 1974, 1982\n\n'''Individual'''\n* [[World Cup Golden Boot|FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe]]: 1974\n* [[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|FIFA World Cup All-Star Team]]: [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]]\n* [[Pi\u0142ka no\u017cna magazine plebiscite|Polish Footballer of the Year]]: 1977, 1981\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Grzegorz Lato}}\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/lato-intl.html International appearances and goals]\n* [http://www.planetworldcup.com/LEGENDS/lato.html Profile and image of Lato]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box |\n |before=Robert Zaw\u0142ocki\n |title=President of [[Polish Football Association]]\n |years=30 October 2008 \u2013 26 October 2012\n |after=[[Zbigniew Boniek]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Awards\n|bg = Gold\n|fg = Navy\n|list1 =\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe]]|before=[[Gerd M\u00fcller]] |after=[[Mario Kempes]]|years=[[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{FIFA World Cup top scorers}}\n{{1974 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{Ekstraklasa top scorers}}\n{{Polish Footballer of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Poland squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #D4213D\n|bordercolor=\n|list1=\n{{Poland Squad 1972 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Poland Squad 1974 World Cup}}\n{{Poland Squad 1976 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Poland Squad 1978 World Cup}}\n{{Poland Squad 1982 World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Kavala F.C. managers}}\n{{Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a managers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lato, Grzegorz}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Malbork]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Polish footballers]]\n[[Category:K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen players]]\n[[Category:Stal Mielec players]]\n[[Category:Atlante F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Poland]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Poland]]\n[[Category:1974 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Poland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Poland 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Democratic Left Alliance politicians]]\n[[Category:Ekstraklasa players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Polish football managers]]\n[[Category:Amica Wronki managers]]\n[[Category:Stal Mielec managers]]\n[[Category:Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a managers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Polonia Restituta (1944\u20131989)]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pomeranian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer managers in Canada]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Grzegorz Lato\n| image              = File:Grzegorz Lato (1974).png \n| imagesize          = 250\n| caption            = Lato in 1974\n| order              =\n| office             = Senator of [[Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n| term_start         = 2001\n| term_end           = 2005\n| predecessor        = J\u00f3zef Fr\u0105czek\n| successor          = W\u0142adys\u0142aw Ortyl\n| order2             = 25th\n| office2            = President of the PZPN\n| term_start2        = 30 October 2008\n| term_end2          = 26 October 2012\n| predecessor2       = Robert Zaw\u0142ocki\n| successor2         = [[Zbigniew Boniek]]\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1950|4|8|67}}\n| birth_place        = [[Malbork]], Poland\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| height             = 1.75 m\n| nationality        = [[Polish people|Polish]]\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Footballer]] (retired)\n* [[Manager (association football)|Football manager]] (retired)\n* [[Politician]]\n* Football administrator\n}}\n| signature          =\n| signature_alt      =\n| module             =\n{{Infobox football biography | embed = yes | header-color = lavender\n| position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| years1         = 1966\u20131980| clubs1 = [[Stal Mielec]]| caps1 = 295| goals1 = 117\n| years2         = 1980\u20131982| clubs2 = [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|Lokeren]]| caps2 = 64| goals2 = 12\n| years3         = 1982\u20131984| clubs3 = [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]]| caps3 = 45| goals3 = 16\n| years4         = 1984\u20131991| clubs4 = Polonia Hamilton| caps4 = 52| goals4 = 20\n| totalcaps      = 456 | totalgoals = 165\n| nationalyears1 = 1971\u20131984| nationalteam1 = [[Poland national football team|Poland]]|nationalcaps1 = 100| nationalgoals1 = 45\n| manageryears1 = 1988\u20131990 | managerclubs1 = [[North York Rockets]]\n| manageryears2 = 1991\u20131993 | managerclubs2 = [[Stal Mielec]]\n| manageryears3 = 1993\u20131995 | managerclubs3 = Olimpia Pozna\u0144\n| manageryears4 = 1995\u20131996 | managerclubs4 = [[Amica Wronki]]\n| manageryears5 = 1996\u20131997 | managerclubs5 = [[Stal Mielec]]\n| manageryears6 = 1997      | managerclubs6 = [[AO Kavala]]\n| manageryears7 = 1999      | managerclubs7 = [[RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a|Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|POL}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 West Germany]]|}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 Spain]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Munich]] | [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Football at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n}}\n}}\n[[File:Grzegorz Lato medal & autograph.jpg|thumb|270px| Copy of G.Lato medal and autograph in '' [[:pl:Aleja Gwiazd Sportu w Dziwnowie|Sports Star Avenue in Dziwn\u00f3w]] '']]\n\n'''Grzegorz Boles\u0142aw Lato''' (born 8 April 1950) is a Polish former professional [[Association football|football]]er and [[Manager (association football)|manager]] who played as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]]. He was a member of Poland's golden generation of football players who rose to fame in the 1970s and early 80s. Over a decade, he represented Poland at 5 major tournaments starting with Gold at the Summer Olympic Games in Munich in 1972 and ending with a third-place finish at the 1982 FIFA World Cup in Spain. He reached the peak of his career at the [[Football World Cup 1974|1974 World Cup]], where he was the [[World Cup Golden Boot|leading scorer]] and the only Pole to-date to have won the honor. After retiring from his playing career he had a brief stint as manager in several clubs in and out of Poland. \n\nLato, as a member of [[Democratic Left Alliance]], was a Polish Senator for the Rzeszow region, between 2001 and 2005. \n\nOn 30 October 2008, he was elected president of [[Polish Football Association]] (PZPN). As president of the PZPN he oversaw the Euro 2012 tournament, which was co-hosted by Poland. He was finally succeeded by [[Zbigniew Boniek]] on 26 October 2012.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Stal Mielec===\nLato was born in [[Malbork]]. He arrived at [[Stal Mielec]] as a teenager in 1966. Over the next 14 years, he led Stal from the Second Division to the top tier of Polish football and its most successful era in its history. During his time there, the club would go on to win the [[Ekstraklasa]]--the Polish First-Division--twice, in 1973 and 1976, as well as be regular participants in European competitions. This era of success culminated with their appearance at the quarter-finals of the [[1975-76 UEFA Cup]]. He inspired the club's good form with his prolific goal scoring, amassing 111 goals in 272 appearances. He was the top scorer of the Ekstraklasa during the 1972-73 and 1974-75 seasons.\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1980, having turned 30, Lato was finally free to leave Poland to pursue his career abroad. Despite his age, his international performances had garnered him interest. Lato ended up receiving a personal invitation from [[Pel\u00e9]] to play for the [[New York Cosmos (1971\u20131985)|New York Cosmos]]. However, he ultimately decided on settling in Belgium playing for [[K.S.C. Lokeren]], scoring 12 goals over 2 seasons. By 1982, Lato decided to move on, signing for [[Atlante F.C.]] in [[Mexico]] where he amassed 15 goals. He spent the rest of the 1980s playing amateur football in [[Hamilton, Ontario]] for Polonia Hamilton--a club founded by Polish immigrants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://poloniahamilton.ca/calendar/|title=HISTORY|date=3 February 2015|website=HAMILTON POLONIA F.C.|language=en-US|access-date=16 February 2019}}</ref> In 1991 he decided to retire from football. \n\n==International career==\nLato represented the [[Poland national football team|Polish national team]] for 13 years during the 1970s and 80s earning a total of 100 caps. He won his first cap under legendary Poland coach [[Kazimierz G\u00f3rski]] in a qualifying game for the [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972 European Championships]] against West-Germany. The game ended as 1\u20133 loss. He was able to translate his prolific domestic goal-scoring record onto the international stage, where he became renowned for his striking prowess, especially in big games.\n\n===World Cup===\n\n====1974 World Cup====\nThe highpoint of Lato's professional career came during the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]] in West Germany. Poland had a tough first round, having been seeded in Group 4, along with Argentina and Italy as well as Haiti. Lato went on to have immediate impact. In Poland's first game against Argentina, he scored 2 goals leading Poland to a historic 3\u20132 win. Buoyed, Poland hammered Haiti in the next game 7\u20130, with Lato adding another 2 goals. Finally Poland beat Italy 2\u20131, to end the group-stage as undefeated winners of Group 4.\n\nIn the second round, Poland were seeded into Group B with West Germany, Sweden and Yugoslavia. Lato continued his great form as the tournament progressed. Poland defeated Sweden 1\u20130 and Yugoslavia 2\u20131, with Lato contributing the winning goals in both games. Poland's final game of the group of was against West Germany. The Germans had also defeated Sweden and Yugoslavia, tying both teams on points. Thus, the game would prove decisive in deciding who would finish Group B 1st or 2nd--the winner would go to the final, the loser would go to the third-place play-off. Poland played a strong game, often threatening the West-German goal. However, Lato was unable to score and Poland succumbed to a 1\u20130 defeat--their only loss of the tournament.\n\nPoland's final game of the tournament was the third-place playoff against holders Brazil. In a tight game, Lato again proved to be the difference, scoring the only goal and leading the Polish national team to a Bronze finish. He ended the tournament as [[FIFA World Cup awards|top goalscorer]], having scored 7 goals.\n\n====1978 World Cup====\nLato had arguably had been Poland's best player at the 1974 World Cup. However, by the time of the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 tournament]] in Argentina he was unable to replicate his great form. In the first round, Poland were seeded in Group 2 with West Germany, Mexico and Tunisia. Poland did well, winning the group by drawing 0\u20130 with West Germany, and winning against Tunisia and Mexico, 1\u20130 and 3\u20131 respectively. Lato, however, was only able to score one goal, albeit a decisive one against Tunisia.\n\nIn the second round, Poland found themselves in the \"group of death\" against Argentina and Brazil--both tournament favorites--and Peru. Lato, unfortunately, couldn't resurrect his from four years prior, only mustering a single goal against Brazil. Poland ultimately finished third place having been beaten by both the hosts Argentina and Brazil 0\u20132 and 1\u20133 respectively. Poland managed to beat Peru 1\u20130 but that wasn't enough to secure 2nd place in Group B and they were duly eliminated. Having played in all of Poland's 6 games, Lato ended the tournament with only 2 goals.\n\n====1982 World Cup====\nLato was 32 by the time Poland qualified for the 1982 FIFA World Cup in Spain. His age was getting the better of him and he lacked the electrifying pace that defined his earlier career. Lato was still a first team player, but during Poland's 8 games at the tournament he managed only a solitary goal in Poland's 5\u20131 thrashing of Peru in the first round. However, several players had risen in a new generation of great Polish players, chief among them [[Zbigniew Boniek]]--who scored a hat-trick against Belgium--were able to fill the void. Despite his lack of goals Lato still contributed to the team play and played and important role. In the end, Poland reached the third-place playoff against France. They went on to win 3\u20132 and Lato added another Bronze World Cup medal to his collection.\n\n===Olympic Games===\nLato won medals at two Summer Olympics football competitions: a [[gold medal]] at the [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Summer Olympics]] and a [[silver medal]] at the [[Football at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHis final game before retirement was on 17 April 1984, a friendly against Belgium. He was subbed off in the 85th and Poland lost the game 0\u20131. Lato amassed 45 goals and the third highest goal scoring total in Polish national team history, second only to that of [[Robert Lewandowski]] and [[W\u0142odzimierz Luba\u0144ski]]. He also had an impressive goal scoring record of 0.43 goals per game.[http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/060412/1/6ixx.html] He was the first Polish player to reach a century of caps.\n\n==Managerial career==\n[[File:Grzegorz Lato by Slawek.jpg|thumb|left|Grzegorz Lato (2010)]]\nIn 1996 he graduated from the School of Coaches of the [[PZPN|Polish Football Association]]. After finishing his football career, he became a coach. Initially, he coached in Canada where he became manager of North York Rockets(1988\u20131990). He then returned to his old club [[Stal Mielec]] (1991\u20131993 and 1996\u20131997) before coaching several other Polish clubs: [[Olimpia Pozna\u0144]] (1993\u20131995) and [[Amica Wronki]] (1995\u20131996). He had a brief stint in Greece as manager of [[Kavala F.C.|AO Kavala]] (1997) before he finally returned to Poland and eventually retired from managing with [[Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] (1999).[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-N0706-0040, Fu\u00dfball-WM, VR Polen - Brasilien 1-0.jpg|thumb|240px|Lato (left) and Brazil's [[Marinho Chagas]] in [[Munich]] during the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]]]]\n\n==After football==\nLato, as a member of [[Democratic Left Alliance]], was a Polish Senator for the Rzeszow region, between 2001 and 2005. \n\nIn October 2008, he was elected President of the [[Polish Football Association|Polish FA]] (PZPN).\nIn an 2011 interview, Lato said that if Poland didn't progress to the Euro 2012 quarterfinals he would hand in his resignation from the position of President of the [[Polish Football Association|Polish FA]]. After Poland's 0\u20131 defeat by the Czech Republic on 16 June 2012--which officially knocked them out of [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] in the group stages--he refused to resign. He did not seek reelection and was replaced by Zbigniew Boniek, on October 2012.\n\n==Playing style==\nBlessed with remarkable acceleration, the talented right-winger consistently lived up to the high expectations placed upon him at the international level. Lato was not renowned as a crowd pleaser, but rather as a consistent team player. His great awareness on the pitch, coupled with his flexibility--he often played as a forward--allowed him to achieve success at the international and club levels. \n\n==Career statistics==\n'Source:<ref>{{NFT|17448|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"12\"|[[Stal Mielec]]\n|1969\u20131970\n|[[Ekstraklasa]]\n|18||6\n|-\n|1970\u20131971\n|Ekstraklasa\n|||11\n|-\n|1971\u20131972\n|Ekstraklasa\n|||\n|-\n|1972\u20131973\n|Ekstraklasa\n|24||13\n|-\n|1973\u20131974\n|Ekstraklasa\n|||13\n|-\n|1974\u20131975\n|Ekstraklasa\n|||19\n|-\n|1975\u20131976\n|Ekstraklasa\n|30||14\n|-\n|1976\u20131977\n|Ekstraklasa\n||||\n|-\n|1977\u20131978\n|Ekstraklasa\n||||\n|-\n|1978\u20131979\n|Ekstraklasa\n||||\n|-\n|1979\u20131980\n|Ekstraklasa\n||||\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!295||117\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|KSC Lokeren]]\n|1980\u20131981\n|[[Belgian Pro League]]\n|33||6\n|-\n|1981\u20131982\n|Belgian Pro League\n|31||6\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!64||12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]]\n|1982\u20131983\n|[[Liga MX]]\n|36||15\n|-\n|1983\u20131984\n|Liga MX\n|5||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!41||16\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Polonia Hamilton||52||20\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total||452||165\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Goal !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || 19 August 1973 || [[Varna]], Bulgaria || {{fb|Bulgaria}} || 2\u20130 || Friendly\n|-\n| 2 || 19 August 1973 || Varna, Bulgaria || {{fb|Bulga